What happens when the Fed raises interest rates
There will be an increase in rates, and the bull market will stumble, bond yields will rise, and the economy will fall into recession.
This we know.
What we don&#39;t know is how long it will take before the onset, and how long it will last.
Specifically for the economy, history explains little about time.
The recession came just 11 months after the first rate hike and for a full 86 months.
The Fed&#39;s rigidity in raising rates often, though not always, determines how the economy and financial assets react.
That is why the administration of the US Central Bank is so emphatic that investors should not focus on when it will start raising rates, but on how long the adjustment will take.
Indeed, there are many variables in the game.
In the end, however, market participants may find that all the fuss about rate hikes is exaggerated.
&quot;The first rate hike by the Fed with the onset of the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as signaling the end of the era of &#39;cheap money,&#39;&quot; Julian Jessop, chief international economist at Capital Economics, told clients.
On the contrary, we do not expect that the gradual return of US interest rates to more normal, but still low levels, will be the seismic impulse that many fear.
This does not mean, however, that there will be no consequences.
Here is a look at how some areas of the economy may have reacted depending on historical trends:
As the market has seen over the past month or so, waiting for rate hikes can lead to volatility for a while.
When the rate is raised, however, the consequences are usually not so dramatic.
&quot;Equity earnings do not appear to have stalled for 12 to 24 months after the first bounce, which, again, likely reflects a delay in monetary policy,&quot; Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study of the results of the Federal Reserve&#39;s rate hike.
More specifically, the market over the past 35 or so years is more likely to reverse sharply - about 14 percent - upwards in rates, remains fairly flat for 250 days thereafter (2.6 percent average increase), then returns to normal after 500 days. with an average return of 14.4 percent over the last six cycles, according to a recent analysis by Bob Doll, chief equity strategist at Nuveen Asset Management, published in Barron&#39;s.
Deutsche says the result for equities tends to take a while to become more pronounced in the rate hike phase, and equity earnings start to decline.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but rate hikes often play into them.
In this case, the Federal Reserve is placed in conditions that did not exist before and could accelerate the recession.
Basically, the gross domestic product will be close to its lowest point ever since the hike.
In 118 rate hikes since 1950, only twice nominal annual GDP has been below 4.5 percent, according to Deutsche Bank.
Even though it was 3.6 percent in the second quarter of 2015, few believe that it will be for a long time, while in the third quarter it remains at a level of only 1.5 percent, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Raising rates amid such a volatile economic backdrop could be risky and raises the question &quot;whether this time will be different,&quot; Deutsche said.
Market participants have been gearing up for a rate hike by the Federal Reserve all year long, with their eyes fixed on the Federal Open Market Committee meeting that ends on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe that the FOMC may have approved a rate hike at this meeting, futures trading suggests only a 25 percent chance.
&quot;In our study from 1950, all rate hikes to date have been in a supercycle of increasing financial leverage, with GDP overlapping pre-recession peaks very quickly after the start of recovery,&quot; the report says.
In contrast, it was an extremely slow recovery from the worst recession in the selected period.
The current cycle is currently the longest the Fed has seen since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, in total it has been going on for 74 months and has not yet ended.
Fixed income has also become volatile as the market anticipates rate hikes, a scenario somewhat similar to that of equities.
The fundamental difference is that for bonds, the effect will come faster than for stocks when the Federal System changes its strategic course.
In the case of bonds, yields seem to reverse vector immediately after the first rate hike/cut in the cycle.
At the end of the rate hike cycle, bond yields immediately fall, Deutsche reports.
Strategists at Charles Schwab believe the rate hike will cause long-term and short-term bond yields to converge, flattening the curve.
High-yield bonds often perform better in this climate, although &quot;we are still wary of yield fluctuations,&quot; Cathy Jones, a fixed income analyst at Schwab, said in a study.
Interestingly, Jones believes that the markets have already adjusted to the expected outcome of the Fed&#39;s policies.
&quot;In addition to a stronger dollar and falling inflation expectations, there are signs that the market has adjusted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy,&quot; she wrote.
Interest rates on short-term loans have risen, the yield curve has flattened, credit spreads have widened, volatility has risen - all characteristics of a market with a tightening of Fed policy.
Generally speaking, companies with a core business in the US will benefit from higher interest rates, and local products will become more attractive.
International companies with lots of debt will be worse off as the rising dollar makes their products more expensive in the global marketplace and their debt more expensive in the financial arena.
&quot;History shows that &#39;quality&#39; stocks outperform market within three months of the initial rate hike,&quot; Goldman Sachs analysts said in a note to clients.
Financially sound companies outperformed financially unstable companies in each rate increase in 1994, 1999 and 2004 by an average of 5 percentage points.
Companies with high returns on equity, as well as stocks with low volatility, also outperformed low-quality stocks by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points), respectively.
Debt will become a big issue.
Companies with a high percentage of floating rate debt will lose the most, according to Goldman.
In addition to pure stock deals, consumers will benefit from a rising dollar.
Investors could also see profits through higher yields, although experts disagree on how quickly this will happen.
