Vangelis Meimarakis: &quot;Europe wants to help us.&quot;
Vangelis Meimarakis served for a number of years in center-right governments that, according to leftists, led the country into a financial crisis.
Now, having become the interim leader of the New Democracy party, he is challenging Tsipras.
A few days before the election, he met with a Euronews journalist.
Euronews: Mr. Meimarakis, welcome to Euronews!
Vangelis Meimarakis: Thank you for the invitation.
euronews: Nine months ago your party suffered a crushing defeat to the SYRIZA coalition, but now, judging by the polls, New Democracy has equaled its popularity.
What has changed during this time?
Vangelis Meimarakis: Greece has changed, and so have we.
Mr. Tsipras lied a lot last January.
Greece was running a budget surplus nine months ago and looking forward to economic growth.
Now the country is again running a budget deficit and high unemployment.
The investors left because Mr. Tsipras drove them away.
Over the past nine months, the Greeks have had the opportunity to assess the situation in which the country was in January, and the false promises of Mr. Tsipras.
And now they can easily compare what was promised with what actually happened.
Daily life has become noticeably worse compared to January, when the situation improved, and this was the case for the majority of Greek citizens.
euronews: But you say that if you win the election, you will seek alliances with other parties, including SYRIZA.
Vangelis Meimarakis: The point is that, as we have learned in recent years, Greece cannot move forward without understanding and cooperation.
And it is no coincidence that in all other countries where rescue programs were or are still in operation, the political forces and all the ruling parties have come together to implement the program on which they have agreed, without giving up their political or ideological autonomy.
That is why I firmly believe that at this stage only the cooperation of political forces and institutions will allow the country to move forward.
euronews: Your party voted in favor of an agreement between Mr Tsipras and the country&#39;s creditors.
If you become the new prime minister on Monday, will you honor this agreement, or will you try to change it, at least in part?
Vangelis Meimarakis: In fact, we voted for the movement of Greece along the European path, because we have a good idea of what disastrous consequences a country&#39;s exit from the EU would lead to.
Now Europe is helping us by providing subsidies to our farmers for their products, we have solidarity funds, the Juncker package and assistance in the banking sector.
All this would be lost if there were no treaty with Europe.
But the current austerity measures were the result of the way Mr Tsipras negotiated.
I know that Europe does not want to destroy us.
Europe wants to help us.
Thus, if Europe sees that the new Greek government during the first year in power wants to restore order, act rationally and make it clear that the country has a strong political will to implement the rescue program, then, I am sure, all the commitments made that are not can be met due to the fact that they lead to a recession, can again be the subject of negotiations, but only after a certain time.
It would be a mistake to believe that already in the first year of the new agreement, we will be able to return to negotiations with our creditors, as they expect full implementation of the agreement.
If we are to win back their trust, we must continue with the privatizations, reforms and structural changes that have been agreed, while continuing to enjoy the benefits of EU funding and the great investment opportunities we must open up for a better understanding and cooperation with Europe.
Unfortunately, during the negotiations, the Tsipras government did not present any serious arguments on many key political issues, which we found out when discussing these issues with our European colleagues.
I can give an example related to the income of farmers.
We have explained to our European partners that this is not a fixed monthly income and therefore cannot be fully taxed in advance.
We were told that the Tsipras ministers had never spoken about it.
That is, the Greek ministers were unprepared and ill-informed, and therefore unsuccessfully negotiated and concluded an unsuccessful agreement.
euronews: If you win the election, you will soon find yourself at the same table as Mr. Juncker, Hollande, Ms. Merkel and other European leaders.
Will what you tell them differ from what your predecessor Antonis Samaras told them?
Vangelis Meimarakis: First of all, I will explain to them that until the end of 2014, we tried to best implement the 2012 agreement, bypassing the sharp corners in it.
We have pushed reforms forward.
Of course, we lacked the necessary decisiveness and speed, but we acted in emergency circumstances.
The market fell and there were no potential buyers willing to pay a price that suited the Greek government.
At that time I was the Speaker of the Parliament, I managed to agree on the opinions of the three parliamentary groups, which then constituted the government majority.
And despite their serious ideological differences on key bills, we had a functioning parliament, and this in the presence of populists and extremists, as well as mass demonstrations taking place outside.
And we have succeeded in bringing the country back to normal, which would continue to improve if the process had not been interrupted by the early general elections that resulted from the December presidential elections.
euronews: In recent weeks, a massive flow of refugees has been moving through Greece.
What do you think about this situation, and about the reaction of the European countries that these people are striving for?
Vangelis Meimarakis: The refugee crisis is a ticking time bomb that we will have to deal with after we win the elections.
And the reason is that the government of SYRIZA did not act in this situation as it should.
In such matters, you should be proactive, because if the problem catches up with you, then only emergency measures remain.
And now we are in such a situation.
Even the interim government that replaced SYRIZA did more in just seven days than Mr. Tsipras did in seven months.
I am sure that these actions of the interim government, which is receiving valuable assistance from the President of the Republic, who called for an EU summit, will make it possible to find a solution.
We need to see how many refugees can leave the country, and mind you - refugees are not illegal immigrants.
These are victims of the war in Syria, victims of some extraordinary events that happened to them.
This issue has a deeply humanitarian aspect, and we will adhere to the position that European politicians must take in this new situation.
An appropriate decision must be made at the EU summit, and the United Nations must be involved.
We also need better coordination, more efficient border controls and refugee reception centers.
We must also make effective use of the economic assistance we receive from the EU in order to be able to deal with this pressing problem.
euronews: Mr. Meimarakis, thank you for the interview.
Vangelis Meimarakis: Thank you.
