It was a tough choice, Cameron wrote in a commentary posted on the SuperCamps website, and continues: &quot;This is a fun, touching, unusual story with a strong message that I love reading to my kids because it always comes up with some image or message that we skip.&quot;
And all is well, except for the last paragraph, in which Cameron is supposed to be retelling the contents of the book, but is actually telling the plot of the 2012 film of the same name, with new characters and details added to diversify the rather short original narrative.
&quot;In the walled city of Vsemnuzhville, where there was no greenery and even air was sold for money, a boy named Ted hopes to win the heart of Audrey - the girl of his dreams, by fulfilling her desire - to see a real tree,&quot; we read in the text a description of a love story , unknown to Dr. Seuss (real name Theodor Seuss Geisel), who died in 1991.
