Experts criticize Public Health England review of e-cigarettes
Claims by the government-funded agency that e-cigarettes are 95% less harmful than smoking came from a meeting of 12 people, some of whom are affiliated with the tobacco industry, the researchers said.
Experts published in the British Medical Journal (BMJ) with the Lancet have criticized the evidence used by Public Health England (PHE) in their e-cigarette report.
PHE published a major milestone report last month, calling it a &quot;comprehensive review of the evidence.&quot;
But some researchers questioned the validity of the data and pointed to some experts&#39; links to the tobacco industry.
An editorial in the Lancet medical journal last month criticized the &quot;extremely shaky argument&quot; on which PHE based its main conclusion.
In the BMJ article, two other researchers questioned whether these claims had &quot;solid or shaky grounds&quot;.
Martin McKee, Lecturer in European Health Organization at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, and Simon Capewell, Lecturer in Clinical Epidemiology at the University of Liverpool, said: &quot;A fundamental principle of public health is that rules must be based on evidence of effectiveness.&quot;
The public expects PHE&#39;s claims that &quot;the current best estimate shows that e-cigarettes are about 95% less harmful than tobacco smoking&quot; to be based on a detailed analysis of the evidence and modeling, they said.
In fact, this is inferred from a single meeting of 12 people who met to develop a multi-criteria decision analysis model in order to summarize their views on the harms associated with various nicotine-containing products; the results of the meeting are summarized in a scientific publication.
McKee and Capewell reported that one of the sponsors of the meeting was a company called EuroSwiss Health, whose CEO was reported to have previously received funding from British American Tobacco for independent research.
He also validated BAT certifications in healthcare in a sustainability report.
One of the 12 people at the meeting announced funding from the e-cigarette maker, with no mention of the funding he had previously reportedly received from tobacco company Philip Morris.
A reasonable explanation for the choice of council members was not provided, but among them there are several well-known e-cigarette advocates, some of whom also announced industry funding in the publication.
It is not known if the other participants in the meeting have experience in tobacco management.
The meeting was also attended by the Head of Tobacco at PHE.
A scientific paper published by the group &quot;graciously agrees&quot; that there is a lack of &quot;strong evidence for the harmful effects of most products by most criteria,&quot; McKee and Capewell wrote.
However, none of these links and limitations were touched upon in the PHE report.
McKee and Capwell said that PHE&#39;s claims that &quot;there is currently no evidence that e-cigarettes are expensive to cause children or non-smokers to smoke&quot; are premature.
Prof. Kevin Fenton, head of health and wellness at PHE, said the BMJ&#39;s claims have been answered in the past.
He said: &quot;Electronic cigarettes are significantly less harmful than tobacco smoking.&quot;
One in two lifelong smokers died of his addiction.
All evidence implies that the health risks from e-cigarettes are relatively small, but we must continue to study the long-term effects.
PHE has a clear duty to inform the public about what the evidence does and does not prove, especially where the public had doubts about the relative danger compared to tobacco.
Around 80,000 people a year die from smoking-related illnesses, and smoking costs the NHS £2bn a year.
By making clear the obvious - that while e-cigarettes are not safe, they only do a fraction of the harm that smoking does - we are fulfilling our mission as a nation.
