&quot;Sonogenetics&quot; allows you to control brain cells using sound waves
The video shows how the nematodes change direction when they are exposed to sound pulses.
Scientists have developed worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can be controlled using pulses of sound waves.
Tiny nematodes change direction the moment they are exposed to sound pulses too high for the human ear to hear.
The impulses act by activating neurons genetically modified to use membrane channels that respond to ultrasonic waves.
More on the topic: Researchers control brain activity with light
The scientists said the worms are demonstrating the possibilities of a new technique called &quot;sonogenetics,&quot; which uses ultrasound to excite certain cells in the brain, heart, and muscles, while the source of ultrasound is located outside the body.
Shrikant Chalasani, a research fellow at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, Calif., told the Guardian that the technique could one day replace deep brain stimulation, an invasive procedure that sends electrical impulses to a person&#39;s brain and is used to treat Parkinson&#39;s disease.
Nematode worms do not normally respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that they did respond when they were placed in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
He found that the bubbles amplify the ultrasonic waves, which then enter the body of the worms.
Amplified ultrasonic waves act on structures called &quot;TRP-4 ion channels&quot; found in the membranes of some worm cells.
Ultrasonic waves cause these ion channels to open and excite the cells associated with them, according to a report in Nature Communications.
To create ultrasound-guided nematodes, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that their motor neurons used TRP-4 ion channels.
During the use of ultrasound to influence modified organisms, sound waves were amplified by microscopic bubbles and injected into the organisms of worms, activating the modified motor neurons.
This technique is similar to that used in &quot;optogenetics&quot; - a new direction that allows scientists to turn neurons on and off using light pulses.
Chalasani argues that sonogenetics may have some advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which is delivered to the desired area of the brain via fiber optics, low-frequency ultrasonic waves pass unhindered through the tissues of the body, so they do not need to go inside the skull to deliver them.
&quot;We believe that for the treatment of certain neurological diseases in the clinical setting, the use of gene therapy and therapeutic viruses can temporarily make human neurons sensitive to the ultrasound signal,&quot; Chalasani said.
He added that, in addition, the technique can be applied to muscle and insulin-producing cells.
