The winner was determined only in the last round, and it was the Russian Mikhail Antipov, who nevertheless managed to catch up with the Pole Jan-Krzysztof Duda, who seemed to be confidently moving towards the title.
The Ukrainian chess player Natalia Buksa celebrated the victory among the girls.
The World Chess Championship, which has been held since early September in Khanty-Mansiysk, seemed to have lost almost all the intrigue by the middle of the tournament distance, since the representative of Poland, Jan-Krzysztof Duda, who issued a series of four victories (competitions are held according to the Swiss system in 13 rounds) confidently took the lead.
Considering that Duda was the rating favorite for the championship, and is generally considered one of the most promising young chess players, the likelihood that he would miss the lead he gained seemed very small.
And even when Duda slowed down and allowed the Russian Mikhail Antipov to close the gap to just 0.5 points, he remained the clear favorite in the fight for the title.
After all, Antipov, in order to catch up with the leader, had to win in the 13th round without fail.
But even that wouldn&#39;t help if Duda won his game.
Plus, this obligatory victory, of course, could affect the game of the Russian chess player and lead to unnecessary mistakes.
Fortunately, Mikhail Antipov managed to avoid them.
He confidently dealt with Francesco Rambaldi, after which he had to wait for Duda, who faced Benjamin Bock, to complete his game.
Fortunately for Antipov, the Polish chess player ended the confrontation with the Dutchman in a draw.
Thus, Antipov and Duda scored an equal number of points - 10 out of 13 possible each, but Antipov had the best additional indicators.
That is why the leadership of the Khanty-Mansiysk Autonomous Okrug, whose governor Natalya Komarova traditionally pays great attention to the development of chess in the region, awarded him the main prize.
But in the girls&#39; competition, there was no intriguing ending.
Tournament leader - Natalia Buksa (Ukraine) - to win the title it was enough not to lose in the last round, which she did with success.
Thus, the victory of the Russian Alina Bivol did not allow her to catch up with Buksa.
The Russian athlete remained second, 0.5 points behind the champion.
