Kyiv broke the atomic union.
Kyiv officially issued Ukraine&#39;s refusal to cooperate with Russia on the completion of the Khmelnitsky nuclear power plant.
The Verkhovna Rada on Wednesday, on the second attempt, still voted to terminate the agreement with Moscow.
Agreements on the completion of the third and fourth units were signed back in 2010-2012, but the project was never launched.
On Wednesday, the Verkhovna Rada of Ukraine adopted a law terminating the agreement concluded in 2010-2012 with the Russian Federation on the construction of the third and fourth units at the Khmelnytsky NPP.
It was possible to carry out the bill introduced by the government of the country only from the second vote, for the first time it was supported by 210 deputies with the required minimum of 226, but then, during the second vote, 234 members of parliament spoke in favor of the draft.
The Khmelnitsky nuclear power plant, laid down in the USSR, according to the original project, was supposed to have four power units of 1 GW each with VVER-type reactors, but only two managed to be built.
Negotiations with Moscow on the completion of the construction led to the conclusion of an intergovernmental agreement by 2010, in 2011-2012 the Rada adopted the relevant laws.
Since there were no funds in the budget of Ukraine, it was assumed that the blocks would have to be built with a loan from the Russian side, but the funds were never allocated.
After the coup in Kiev in February 2014 and the ensuing cooling in relations between the two countries, Kiev began to curtail relations with Moscow in the nuclear industry, announcing its refusal to cooperate on the Khmelnytsky nuclear power plant and on the project to build a nuclear fuel plant in Ukraine.
The only area where relations have been preserved was the purchase of fuel from the Russian Federation for operating Ukrainian nuclear power plants (providing about half of the electricity generation in the country), since so far the Ukrainian NNEGC Energoatom has nothing to replace Russian supplies.
The plans to complete the construction of the Khmelnitsky NPP with another contractor in Ukraine have not yet been finally abandoned: back in 2014, negotiations with the Czech Skoda JS were announced in Kyiv.
