The parties were given mandates.
Yesterday, the election commission of Nizhny Novgorod summed up the results of the elections to the city duma in the municipal district, distributing 12 deputy mandates, played according to party lists.
Traditionally, many complaints about violations during the elections were made by representatives of the Communist Party of the Russian Federation, who accused the election commission of &quot;covering falsifications.&quot;
The opposition&#39;s remarks were not accepted.
At the same time, the electoral committee refused the Communists of Russia party to organize a referendum on the abolition of fees for the overhaul of apartment buildings.
The city electoral committee officially presented the results of the elections to the City Duma of Nizhny Novgorod in the municipal constituency.
In total, 1.03 million people were included in the voter lists in Nizhny Novgorod, 746.7 thousand voters were issued ballots for voting in precinct commissions, and 268 thousand voters voted in the elections.
More than 11.7 thousand ballots were declared invalid, and 24 - lost.
Yesterday, 12 mandates were distributed among political parties, depending on the votes they received.
According to the lists of United Russia, six seats in the City Duma are given to Dmitry Svatkovsky, Dmitry Krasnov, Vasily Shupranov, Elizaveta Solonchenko, Vyacheslav Rasteryaev and Igor Nagorny.
The only mandate of the Liberal Democratic Party was the leader of the party, Vladimir Zhirinovsky.
Two mandates of the Communist Party of the Russian Federation are distributed between Vladimir Bulanov and State Duma deputy Alexander Tarnaev.
Three mandates of A Just Russia go to Alexander Razumovsky, Igor Bogdanov and Mikhail Shalyugin.
Now, within five days, these candidates must decide whether they will work as deputies in the city duma: in case of refusal of the mandate, he passes to the next candidate on the party list.
The chairman of the city electoral committee, Alexander Makeev, informed the members of the commission that he was introducing duty to &quot;send telegrams to Zhirinovsky and others&quot; with a view to refusing mandates.
When approving the protocol on the results of the elections, representatives of the Communist Party announced multiple violations.
Leonid Krasnokutsky, a member of the City Election Committee with an advisory vote from the Communist Party of the Russian Federation, proposed not to recognize the voting results in four constituencies No. 21-24, recalling that by order of the head of the administration of the Sormovsky district, the entrance to the administration building, where four district commissions were located, was closed.
Neither the deputies of the State Duma, nor the candidates themselves, nor observers could get inside for a long time, and the resonant scandal with the storming of the doors of the district administration was shown on television.
At meetings of district commissions, all observers and members of commissions with the right to consultative vote had the opportunity to attend.
Their head stopped access only when the voting ended and the precinct commissions had not yet arrived to hand over their ballots.
This was done in order to prevent various provocations.
&quot;Then the chapter was corrected, and interested persons could be present at all meetings,&quot; Natalya Andryushina, a member of the city election committee, retorted.
The communists objected that Lyudmila Aristova, deputy of the legislative assembly of the region, was illegally detained in the blocked administration building for more than four hours, about which a statement was sent to the investigative committee.
The opposition was also indignant that in a number of PECs on election day they began to seal the ballot boxes at 6-7 in the morning, putting ballots for early voting in them.
At the same time, no one notified the members of the commissions with the right to an advisory vote and observers, so they arrived at the beginning of the elections at 8 am.
Communists are sure that in the morning hours before the opening of polling stations, ballots could be thrown into the ballot boxes uncontrollably.
However, the City Election Committee, which has already considered more than 124 complaints on various occasions, according to Alexander Makeev, did not find any violations with the stuffing of unaccounted ballots.
The members of the commission did not support the proposal of their colleague from &quot;Fair Russia&quot; Maria Popova through the regional election committee to come out with amendments to regional legislation in order to clearly establish the time for opening envelopes with early voting ballots, which then fall into the ballot box.
&quot;On your own initiative, contact the Central Election Commission,&quot; Alexander Makeev advised Mrs. Popova.
At the end of the meeting, Sergei Samokhin, a member of the Communist Party of the Russian Federation, attacked the chairman with loud accusations, shouting that the election commission was ignoring dozens of complaints and covering up electoral fraud.
&quot;You&#39;re not at a rally here, be careful when you say!&quot; - offended the chairman of the electoral committee.
As a result, the protocol was approved almost unanimously.
Until September 27, the electoral commission must approve the general results of the elections, after which the first meeting of the city duma of Nizhny Novgorod of the sixth convocation will be scheduled within three weeks.
In addition to determining the election results, the city election commission refused to register an initiative group for holding a local referendum to the Communists of Russia political party.
Judging by the documents, the party members were going to bring two questions to Nizhny Novgorod for discussion: do they agree that fees for the overhaul of apartment buildings should be &quot;immediately canceled&quot; and tariffs for housing and communal services &quot;frozen until 2020.&quot;
However, the Duma&#39;s lawyer, Irina Maslova, explained that the appeal of the &quot;Communists of Russia&quot; was contrary to the law.
FedEx Revenue Mixed, 2016 Downgraded
FedEx posted disappointing results for the last quarter, and the delivery service giant cut its full-year earnings guidance as demand for freight services slumped and costs rose in its ground transportation division.
The company also said it plans to hire approximately 55,000 seasonal workers for the holidays.
At the same time last year, FedEx said it would hire 50,000 temporary workers for the holidays.
Its shares fell about 2.5 percent in pre-trading 45 minutes before the opening of the exchange on Wednesday.
FedEx Corp. said it expects to earn between $10.40 and $10.90 in the fiscal year ending next May, down 20 cents from its previous forecast.
Analysts were looking at $10.84 according to the FactSet survey.
The downgrade comes despite a rate hike of 4.9 percent on average, which will take effect on January 4, and an increase in ground transportation fees for heavy or oversized cargo, which begins in November.
The company said it still expects revenue to grow year-over-year thanks to cost reductions, higher gross income and growth in online commerce.
Chairman and CEO Fred Smith said the company &quot;performed strongly in light of weaker-than-forecast economic conditions, especially in manufacturing and global trade.&quot;
The holiday hiring plans were announced a day after rival UPS announced that they plan to hire an additional 95,000 employees, about the same number they hired last year.
For the quarter that ended Aug. 31, FedEx made $692 million, up 6 percent from a year earlier.
Earnings per share were $2.42, close to the $2.44 per share average forecast by Zacks Investment Research polling 12 analysts.
Revenue increased 5% to $12.3 billion.
Six analysts polled by Zacks suggested $12.23 billion.
FedEx has suffered in recent years from a downturn in the international express shipping sector, resulting in no gross revenue growth in its express shipping division.
However, the boom in online shopping dramatically improved results at FedEx Ground.
In the most recent quarter, ground transportation revenue rose 29%, but operating income remained broadly flat due to higher costs for large shipments and self-insurance.
The express division saw higher revenue due to higher base rates, while the freight sector lost revenue due to higher labor costs.
In preliminary trading about an hour before the opening of the exchange, FedEx shares fell $3.85, or 2.5 percent, to $150.15.
They closed Tuesday down 11 percent for the year and 17 percent below the June 11 record.
In the most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve officials will spend two days this week at a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table deciding whether it&#39;s time to raise the key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
At one end of an ornate conference room, two stories high, a wall painting of the United States will hang over them.
This card is a reminder that Federal Reserve Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues must put the country&#39;s economic interests ahead of all others.
The central bank has received a double mandate from Congress: to maximize employment in the US and keep prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, the leaders of the Federal System have recognized that there is a third, unwritten mandate: financial stability.
And this third order may be an unknown factor in Thursday&#39;s near-predictable decision about whether the US economy is ready to bounce back from the unprecedented stimulus provided by near-zero short-term interest rates since the end of 2008.
Even though most data show strong growth in the economy, the recent turmoil in global financial markets may deter already cautious Fed officials from adding volatility by raising the federal funds base rate - even by as little as a quarter of a percentage point.
&quot;Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be the first and most important consideration,&quot; said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage Stifel Nicolaus &amp; Co.
&quot;However, I think that if they were looking for a reason not to raise rates, the increased uncertainty around the world market is enough to give them an excuse to wait further,&quot; she said.
There is no consensus on what the Federal Reserve will do, which in itself provokes fluctuations in the financial market.
Roughly half of economists recently polled by Bloomberg were expecting interest rates to rise this week.
Financial markets, however, expect the Fed to hold off, with the key indicator showing only about a 30 percent chance of a quick recovery.
This could send the stock market down if the Fed raises rates, provided decision makers don&#39;t soften the blow with a promise that the next raise won&#39;t be soon.
The Dow rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85 on Tuesday.
The rise was fueled by expectations that Fed strategists will leave rates this week, said John Lonsky, chief economist at Moody&#39;s Capital Markets Research.
&quot;It will be a surprise if the Fed raises rates at this point in time,&quot; he said.
If the Fed does so, &quot;they will have to go far in asserting their strategy to keep the financial markets in their hands so they don&#39;t panic.&quot;
Other experts countered that a rate hike could calm the financial markets, as it would remove uncertainty about how the Federal System would operate.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared to be poised to raise rates by 0.25% this month, taking the first small step in a slow tightening of financial conditions that could confirm the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expects a rate hike this year, despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, labor market growth has been solid this year.
Unemployment fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years, and close to what the Federal system considers full employment.
Wage growth shows signs of acceleration.
And while inflation remains below the central bank&#39;s target of 2% for the year, Federal System officials said the key reason was the temporary effect of the sharp drop in oil prices.
The economy &quot;can handle higher rates, and needs them, given the shrinking labor market,&quot; said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world began to shake at the end of last month, after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones average for industrial stocks fell as much as 16% from a record high in May, as investors feared that a slowdown in the Chinese economy could dampen global growth.
The market has partly rebounded this month and the Dow is now about 10% below its high in May.
For the Fed&#39;s management, market disturbance further complicates the difficult timing of an interest rate hike.
&quot;In the absence of information about what happened in the financial markets and news about the weakness of the Chinese economy in the past few weeks, they would have turned the screws on this meeting,&quot; said Stephen D. Oliner, senior researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former staff member Federal Reserve System.
Now, he predicts, they will wait at least a month to get more control over the consequences.
&quot;There is a lot of uncertainty about what the implications for the US economy could be, and they have little to no hard data after recent events in China,&quot; Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not a primary concern of the Federal System, and technically should not be considered in these decisions.
But in essence, the Federal Reserve System has become the world&#39;s financial power.
The influence of the Central Bank in recent years has been enormous.
A single hint from then-Chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Federal Reserve might &quot;mute&quot; its monetary expansion sent markets around the world into turmoil.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, one would expect Federal Reserve officials not only to monitor developments everywhere, but also to consult with other central bankers and experts to better understand the world economy. .
Their decision-making process is &quot;more of an art than a science,&quot; said Zachary Karabell, CEO of Envestnet Inc, a global wealth management strategy company.
Jeffrey Lucker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Virginia, noted this month that &quot;there have been instances in the history of the Federal Reserve of overreacting to financial market movements that seem to be unrelated to economic principles.&quot;
Lucker, a voting member of the influential Federal Open Market Committee who pushed for a rate hike, cited the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The financial crisis in Asia resulted in the Fed cutting its benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, &quot;despite limited identifiable impacts on US growth,&quot; Lucker said.
A year later, the leaders of the Federal System canceled these reductions.
The Federal Reserve should only prioritize stability concerns in times of major crises, such as the market crash in 2008,&quot; said Adam C. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England&#39;s interest rate committee.
The latest panic never came close to that level, he said.
&quot;You certainly wouldn&#39;t want to be in a situation where you&#39;re scared of rising rates because the markets are going through a turmoil,&quot; said Posen, president of the Institute for World Economics. Peterson.
The Federal Reserve Act is still dual mandated and doesn&#39;t mention financial stability, and until that changes, I don&#39;t think they should be ahead of the curve.
