Four die when police fire rubber bullets at protesters in Nepal
Four people, including a 4-year-old boy, were killed in southern Nepal when police fired rubber bullets into crowds protesting the country&#39;s proposed new constitution, an official said Wednesday.
The violence took place Tuesday evening in Rupandei district, about 175 miles west of Kathmandu, the country&#39;s capital.
Bishnu Prasad Dakal, head of the district police, said more than 1,000 protesters had gathered outside one of the police stations, some throwing rocks and firebombs.
Mr Dakal said the police fired tear gas, then fired into the air before firing rubber bullets.
Twenty police officers and five civilians were injured, he said.
It is not clear why rubber bullets, which are known to kill but are traditionally used as a less lethal alternative, caused such a high death rate.
The clash was the latest in weeks of violent protests in the southern lowlands of Nepal, where the Madesi say the new provinces under the new constitution will diminish their political influence.
Protests have also taken place in western Nepal, among Tharu citizens who want to have their own state.
At least 40 people, including eleven police officers, were killed in violent clashes, starting with 10
August, when the four main political parties signed an agreement to divide the country into provinces, a decisive step towards a new constitution, but a highly contentious issue in Nepal, which had been centrally ruled for several centuries.
Work on a new constitution has been underway since 2008, but lawmakers hastened the process after a devastating earthquake that killed thousands in April.
Lawmakers voted on the articles of the Kathmandu draft constitution this week, and officials said the new chapter would be signed into law by Sunday.
