Diabetics with slight obesity may benefit from obesity surgery
The beneficial effects after obesity surgery in slightly obese people with type 2 diabetes can last at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is still too early to say that slightly obese diabetics live longer after obesity surgery than those who receive non-surgical treatment.
&quot;The death statistics don&#39;t show up right away,&quot; said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an obesity surgery expert who wrote about the new study in an editorial column for JAMA Surgery.
Bariatric surgery, or bariatric surgery, uses various techniques to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the ability of organizations to absorb food.
For several years, bariatric surgery has proven effective for treating type 2 diabetes, but the main studies have been in people with morbid obesity who have a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a measure of weight relative to height, is considered normal between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or higher indicates that a person is overweight, and people with a BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Taiwan&#39;s Min-Sheng General Hospital used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery, gastric bypass and sleeve gastrectomy, with medical treatment for type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The mean BMI of those who underwent surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of their fifth year of participation in the study.
At the same time, the BMI of those who received non-surgical treatment for diabetes remains at about 29.
Among those who underwent surgery, 36% were completely cured of diabetes, and 28% were partially cured.
In the drug-treated group, by comparison, complete cure of diabetes was seen in only 1% and partial cure in only about 2%.
In addition, measures of blood pressure, triglycerides, and &quot;bad&quot; LDL cholesterol &quot;were generally better in the surgical group,&quot; the authors state.
The researchers also monitored blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood sugar levels over time.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7%, the researchers write.
After surgery, mean hemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
In the treatment group, however, it remained stable at about 8%.
But better glycemic control performance, reflected by good hemoglobin A1c levels, did not reduce the death rate in five years, according to research leader Dr Chi-Cheng Su and colleagues.
The research team also compared the mean results of the two types of surgical treatment.
At year 5, compared with the sleeve gastrectomy group, the bypass group lost more weight (18.7 kg vs 14.2 kg), achieved greater reductions in BMI (7.4 vs 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3. 1% versus 2.1%) and was also closer to complete remission of diabetes (46.9% versus 16.7%).
While the new study does not show a life expectancy benefit from surgery beyond five years, there is evidence from a study of overweight people in Sweden that surgery does increase life expectancy, according to Blackstone of the Phoenix College of Medicine. University of Arizona.
Obese people who opted for bariatric intervention were about 29% less likely to die within 15 years, compared with more traditional methods, according to a Swedish study.
Although the new study did not show an increase in life expectancy, Blackstone noted that this is encouraging people with a BMI below 35 interested in such a procedure.
&quot;Here, the report is very important because it states that such surgery is safe in the low BMI group, where there is no increased risk of mortality or kidney disease,&quot; she said.
Blackstone added that people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously as soon as a patient&#39;s BMI falls between 27 and 30.
&quot;I think we&#39;re waiting too long to get people to take this seriously,&quot; she said.
It seems to me that once they accumulate the genetic changes that trigger obesity and diabetes in their bodies, it is very difficult to reverse this.
