Fans from Europe are at risk of becoming homeless.
Only 23 St. Petersburg hotels have the right to host tourists who will come to watch the 2018 FIFA World Cup.
The rest of the hotels are not in a hurry to get the appropriate permission.
According to experts, this is a very worrying sign.
On the eve of the world championship, the authorities will urgently have to figure out how to resettle all the guests of the city.
Interlocutors of &quot;Rosbalt&quot; believe that because of the tournament, the cost of renting rented apartments will increase by 10-30%, and after the championship, you will have to overpay for rented housing.
The World Cup forced the authorities to pay attention to the condition of Russian hotels.
According to the law, written specifically for the championship, each hotel in St. Petersburg must go through a classification procedure and prove that it corresponds to the declared number of stars and the level of service.
It is already clear that not everyone will be able to do this: hoteliers are so afraid of inspections that they often do not even send documents to requests from the Federal Antimonopoly Service for St. Petersburg.
According to the head of the OFAS Vadim Vladimirov, the department has studied 138 hotels and now plans to open 34 cases against hotels, many of which simply did not respond to antimonopoly officials.
There are signs that the management of three dozen companies deceived the townspeople by placing this or that number of stars in advertising, Vladimirov noted.
The problem is that now literally every number counts, not a single one can be lost before 2018.
Officials suspect that fans will occupy all St. Petersburg hotels during the football championship.
Now tourists can count on 30.5 thousand rooms in the city.
According to Smolny, there are 17 five-star hotels in St. Petersburg, 51 four-star hotels, 100 two- and three-star hotels, and 550 one-star hotels.
According to Nana Gvichia, First Deputy Committee for Tourism Development, only 23 hotels have passed the classification at the moment - so many checks have been carried out by companies accredited in St. Petersburg.
But whether any hotel ordered a similar procedure from regional enterprises, Smolny, by an amazing coincidence, is unknown.
That is, there may be more people who have passed the classification, but no one knows about it.
“Over the past six months, hotels have not been very eager to pass the classification,” admitted Ekaterina Shadskaya, director of the North-Western Branch of the Russian Union of Tourism Industry.
This is due to the high season, during which hoteliers earn the most money and do not want to do other things.
Another reason is the budgets that did not include the cost of inspections, while the procedure can cost the hotel, depending on the status, from 30 to 100 thousand rubles or more.
But still, hotel managers have recently become more active and began to apply for classification, Shadskaya assured.
Hotels must be in time before July 1, 2016, otherwise they will not only pay a fine, but also will not receive the right to work at the World Cup.
It is already known that, depending on the star rating, a fixed fee for a hotel room will be developed for the duration of the tournament.
The formulas by which the cost will be calculated will be made public next year.
This was done in order to prevent prices from skyrocketing by 200-300%, as happens, for example, during the St. Petersburg Economic Forum.
You need to have a conscience and not allow a two or three times increase, but hotels also need to be allowed to earn.
&quot;I think the growth will be up to 50%&quot;, - explained the President of the Russian Hotel Association Gennady Lamshin.
In turn, Vadim Vladimirov is not sure that price fixing corresponds to the understanding of a market economy.
I do not know how this fits into the framework of economic theory, but I hope that this measure is justified.
&quot;It&#39;s better than a rampant rise in prices,&quot; he said.
It is not clear what will happen to popular cheap hostels.
State Duma deputies introduced a bill according to which hostels should be prohibited in residential buildings.
We very much hope that this law will not be adopted or will not apply to St. Petersburg.
&quot;We will defend the point of view that hostels should be preserved,&quot; Nana Gvachia believes.
However, according to her, the owners of mini-hotels in any case should be prepared to tighten the Housing Code.
If the State Duma still approves the bill, then about 80% of hostels in St. Petersburg will close, and at the moment they have 1.5 thousand rooms.
According to the President of the Federation of Restaurateurs and Hoteliers of the North-West, Leonid Garbar, there are not enough two- and three-star hotels in St. Petersburg, which are in demand by football fans, but there is a bias towards hotels with four and five stars.
This state of affairs is analogous to the situation when &quot;75 thousand VIPs sit in an 80,000-seat stadium.&quot;
This can be corrected just at the expense of mini-hotels.
The expert considers their possible ban &quot;idiocy&quot;: &quot;It seems strange to me that some people can live in apartments, but for some reason visitors cannot.&quot;
