Quadruple increase in the number of children who swallowed hand sanitizer in the last 4 years
Poison centers in the United States have reported a nearly 400 percent increase since 2010 in the number of children under 12 who have ingested high-alcohol hand sanitizer, according to the Georgia State Poison Control Center.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia State Poison Control Center, cases of ingestion of hand sanitizers reported to poison control centers by children under 12 increased from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
&quot;Children come into contact with these substances more often, and, unfortunately, a certain percentage of them are sent to the emergency room,&quot; Lopez told CNN.
He said that some children drink disinfectant liquid on purpose, and some do it to impress their friends, or to bet on social media.
Videos on Youtube show teenagers drinking disinfectant liquid as cheap booze.
The teens reportedly mixed the disinfectant with an alcohol-based mouthwash to create a stronger drink.
Younger children may be attracted to the pleasant smells of the disinfectant liquid.
&quot;The kid doesn&#39;t think it can hurt him,&quot; Lopez said.
Many of the most addictive (hand sanitizers) are those that are scented.
There are hand sanitizers with the smell of strawberries, grapes, oranges, which are very attractive to children.
Hand sanitizer contains anywhere from 45 to 95 percent alcohol.
In young children, especially, just a few sprays can cause alcohol poisoning.
&quot;It&#39;s a high-strength alcohol,&quot; Dr. Stephen Thornton, chief physician of the poison control center at the University of Kansas Hospital, told Fox 4 in Kansas City.
You wouldn&#39;t just leave a shot of whiskey, but people keep these hand sanitizers in plain sight, and if the kids get to them, it&#39;s a quick way to consume large amounts of alcohol.
Naija Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently ingested about four sprays of strawberry-flavored hand sanitizer at school, was admitted to the ER for treatment.
She had a blood alcohol level of 179, twice that of an adult who is legally considered intoxicated, according to Dr. Chris Ritchie, the emergency physician who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center near Atlanta. .
Naija was confused and unable to walk when she was taken to the emergency room.
Doctors watched her overnight at a separate children&#39;s clinic for any signs of a brain injury, as the alcohol caused the girl to fall and hit her head, Ritchie said.
&quot;It was very scary,&quot; Orthoria Scott, Naiji&#39;s mother, told CNN.
It could well have been fatal to my child.
Lopez recommended that parents and teachers use non-alcoholic agents or disinfectant wipes, in addition to keeping hand sanitizers out of reach of children.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some disinfectant fluids have been linked to death.
In 2013, two Ontario women died after ingesting a disinfectant containing an undeclared toxic ingredient.
Health officials suspect the product contained methanol, the lethal agent, rather than ethyl alcohol, which was listed as the active ingredient.
In January, three fourth-graders in upstate New York conspired to poison their &quot;obnoxious&quot; teacher by &quot;distributing antibacterial substances in the classroom,&quot; according to a police report.
The teacher is severely allergic to hand sanitizers and has banned them from her classroom.
The police believe the failed plan was &quot;blank talk&quot; and are raising discipline issues with the school district.
