News Economics ― Nobel Laureate: Globalization
Print The processes of globalization were supposed to help reduce inequality in the world.
In fact, the situation looks different, the difference in incomes of the population in developing economies, on the contrary, is growing.
Eric Maskin.
To fix this, it is necessary to increase the level of education of low-skilled workers, says Eric Maskin, Chief Researcher at the International Laboratory for Analysis and Choice of Decisions at the Higher School of Economics, 2007 Nobel Prize in Economics.
In the past twenty years, the world has experienced an unprecedented growth in global markets.
Trade borders between countries became more and more open.
Proponents of globalization predicted great benefits for emerging economies.
&quot;And those predictions came true to a large extent,&quot; Maskin emphasizes.
So, for example, China and India received a serious increase in GDP per capita.
However, not everything is so rosy.
It was expected that globalization would close the gap between the &quot;haves&quot; and &quot;have-nots&quot; in poor countries, which is manifested in large income inequality, and more specifically, wage inequality.
But in fact, this inequality has only increased, notes Eric Maskin in his article &quot;Why Global Markets Haven&#39;t Reduced Inequality in Emerging Economies&quot; published in The World Bank Economic Review, which was translated and quoted by the NIE HSE.
Together with the economist, Harvard University professor Michael Kremer, Eric Maskin developed an alternative theory that demonstrates why the income gap in poor countries increases as globalization grows, reminds the NIE HSE.
Specific processes are taking place in the new global market.
To demonstrate them, Maskin identifies four skill levels of specialists - A and B for rich countries, C and D - for poor ones.
After globalization, D specialists from poor countries lack the skill level to compete with A and B specialists from rich countries.
And if level C workers from poor countries have wages growing due to cooperation with B workers from rich countries, then D workers do not feel growth or their wages fall altogether.
The net effect is that the internationalization of production will increase the wage gap between the two categories of professionals in poor countries and, consequently, increase the level of inequality.
Kremer and E. Maskin proposed a surprisingly beautiful model, an alternative to the Ricardian theory of comparative advantage.
It allows us to explain why globalization has led to income inequality,” says Fuad Aleskerov, tenured professor, head of the International Laboratory for Analysis and Decision Choice, head of the Department of Mathematics, National Research University Higher School of Economics.
And like any powerful theory, I&#39;m sure it will lead to a surge of empirical work in this area.
The solution to the problem, according to Eric Maskin, is to increase the level of education of low-skilled workers.
However, the workers themselves, as the scientist notes, do not have the funds for this, and it is unprofitable for companies to pay for their training.
In such a situation, governments, international agencies, NGOs and private foundations can play a significant role, Maskin said.
The scientist notes that the developed theory in no way calls for stopping the process of globalization, which has brought and is bearing fruit in the form of GDP growth in countries.
Derbent: living connection of times.
Derbent, one of the most ancient cities in Russia, celebrates its 2000th anniversary in September.
