This is the oldest mosque in Russia.
The interior is striking in scope and solemnity: the arcades of domes and vaults rest on square columns and are illuminated by the rays of the sun from tiny windows.
Keeping and breeding pigeons is a traditional hobby of the inhabitants of Derbent.
Poultry owners put up dovecotes in yards, under trees, in attics.
A breathtaking sight - a flock of white doves take off into the sky, similar to the flashes of festive fireworks.
In order to defend against the enemy, the ancient Persians blocked the Caspian gates with a double stone wall.
Leaving 500 meters into the sea, this structure blocked the harbor of Derbent.
In 2003, the fortress walls of Derbent were included in the UNESCO World Heritage List as the best preserved monument of ancient Persian fortification architecture.
Carpets were woven in Derbent as far back as the 5th century, and the technology of this unique craft has survived almost unchanged to this day.
On one of the streets adjacent to the city market, carpets for every taste are sold - carpets made of wool, cotton or felt of all colors and shades, with and without pile, with complex ornaments and fancy borders.
The development of the city began with mahals - quarters with one-story stone buildings.
Over the years, the mahals have hardly changed.
Only satellite dishes, air conditioners on the walls and street lights remind you that you are not in a medieval, but in a modern city.
In the old part of the city, details of the aqueduct built by the Persians about a thousand years ago have been preserved.
Ancient springs have survived to this day, in which local residents still draw water today.
Many Derbent residents prefer water from proven historical fountains to ordinary tap water.
In Derbent there was one of the centers of pottery.
Irrigated and painted vases, dishes, jugs, cups were valued throughout the Caucasus.
The hands of potters still make wonderful ceramic products for both practical and souvenir purposes.
During holidays and festivals, crowds of spectators gather under a tightrope, on which students of the Republican School of Circus Art perform.
The history of amazing and risky craftsmanship dates back several centuries.
A new trend is that more and more girls can be seen among tightrope walkers.
In the premises of the former Maiden&#39;s Bath, the Museum &quot;Culture and Life of Ancient Derbent&quot; operates today.
Previously, unmarried girls and brides, accompanied by their friends, washed here, and now anyone can see the vaulted-domed hall, hot and cold pools, bathing accessories that are a thing of the past.
Most houses in Derbent have hot water, but baths and steam rooms are as popular today as they were in the old days.
The benefits of warming the body with steam are written in old books.
After the bath, blood improves, muscles lose fatigue, the body becomes flexible and light.
In the festival &quot;Commonwealth&quot;, which takes place on the territory of the Naryn-Kala fortress, ethno-courtyards from many regions of Dagestan take part.
Participants in national costumes dance, play folk melodies, sing songs of the peoples of the Caucasus and treat visitors to delicious homemade cheese.
Kyrkhlyar is the burial place of forty martyrs who laid down their lives for Islam.
This is one of the most revered complexes for the Muslims of the North Caucasus.
The sarcophagi, yellowed from time to time, are carved from solid stone blocks and oriented, as is customary among the Arabs, along the west-east axis.
Brothers Gavril and Albert Yakubov cut and shave clients in a small salon near the Upper Bazaar.
The barbershop has been at this location for many years.
Barber crafts are passed down from generation to generation.
At the same time, the Yakubov brothers can make not only the traditional, but also the most modern hairstyle.
On one of the streets of the Old Town, a house has been preserved in which the Decembrist writer Alexander Bestuzhev-Marlinsky, exiled to the Caucasus, lived.
Having learned the Turkic language and collected ethnographic material, he described Derbent in the first third of the 19th century with its ancient monuments, life and everyday life of the townspeople.
Chaikhana is a traditional club of the East, where only tea and homemade cakes are served.
Men come here to quench their thirst, chat with friends and solve some work problems.
As in the past, women are not recommended to cross the threshold of the tea house.
The Derbent dance ensemble &quot;Kaspiy&quot; was created three years ago, but has already managed to take part in events of the republican and Russian level.
The soloists of the ensemble rehearse every day, learning to perfection the folk Avar, Dargin, Tat, Armenian dances.
With the onset of the evening, when the noise subsides and the street lights are lit, the locals sit down on benches near the houses with protruding terraces.
As a rule, Derbents discuss everyday issues.
But on the eve of the anniversary, they are increasingly recalling episodes of the unique history of their city, which influenced the fate of the entire Black Sea-Caspian region.
A business &quot;airport game&quot; was held in Domodedovo.
A new form of education is being tested in the capital.
Four hundred students tried themselves as airport employees.
For this, models of three air harbors were mounted in Domodedovo.
Young people not only inspected and registered passengers, but also served aircraft.
All this is in the form of a business game, however, in terms of complexity, it was not inferior to reality.
Late flights, two passengers at once with fractures on board, the ladder was lost somewhere on the way to the plane.
For a real airport - hell.
For the one who settled in the Domodedov hangar - a standard set of tasks that beginners have to solve.
Three large airports from different countries of the world fit in one hangar at once.
Today they employ four hundred students from metropolitan colleges and universities.
An unparalleled chance to learn all about the inner world of an air harbor.
Passenger registration, aircraft maintenance, baggage turnover - they were even entrusted with buses on the airfield, ladders and screening of passengers.
And the passengers are problematic.
One had a mess with his documents, another missed his flight, a third filled his bag with suspicious items.
And you need to deal with all this, as in life - in the shortest possible time.
For each of these completed tasks, they are credited with a certain amount, virtual money, as if the airline had paid them the corresponding amounts for servicing the flight.
&quot;They are fined if they fail to fulfill their respective tasks,&quot; Dmitry Khilko, financial analyst of the game, explains in an interview with the Vesti-Moskva program.
Officials from the Ministry of Education are closely watching what is happening.
For them, this exam is an attempt to try out a new form of learning.
She has already found a place in the course of secondary vocational education.
&quot;Six interregional competence centers will be formed, which will, in fact, become new models for the activities of modern colleges with a modern management system, highly qualified personnel, and modern equipment,&quot; says the director of the Department of State Policy in the Field of Training Workforce and Additional Professional Education of the Russian Ministry of Education and Science Natalya Zolotareva.
But students are not up to global plans.
After three days of such training, they seem to need a day off.
But marks for this examination had quite material expression.
The latest smart glasses, the best I&#39;ve ever seen!
&quot;I received them for responding to the claim against our airport on Instagram in a timely manner,&quot; said Sergey Shuvalov, a participant in the game, PR manager of the Frankfurt Airport team.
The best judges, as they say, were taken on a pencil in order to invite them to work by the time they completed their studies.
The US Embassy regrets the closure of the American Center in Moscow.
The American Embassy in Russia expressed its regret over the closure of the American Center operating at the Library for Foreign Literature.
The Center has been operating in Moscow for over 22 years.
The US Embassy in Moscow deeply regrets the unilateral decision of the Russian government to close the American Center of the US Embassy at the All-Russian State Library. M.I. Rudomino in Moscow.
&quot;The recent unilateral steps taken by the Russian Federation cast doubt on the commitment of the Russian government to the ties between the Russian and American peoples, which have not been interrupted even during the Cold War and other difficult moments in the long history of relations between our countries,&quot; said US Ambassador John Tefft, received by Interfax.
The American Center created deep and strong bonds between the people and cultures of Russia and the United States.
It served as the center of American culture, history, and literature in the Russian capital, and served as a meeting place for numerous American dignitaries, including astronauts, artists, athletes, scientists, politicians, and writers.
&quot;Last year alone, the American Center held more than 400 cultural and educational events and received more than 50,000 Russian visitors,&quot; the diplomat stressed.
Tefft recalled that about a year ago it was decided to close another joint Russian-American project - the FLEX educational exchange program (Future Leaders Exchange Program).
The Green Tribunal turned out to be quick to punish.
A typical situation: four officials are standing in front of the table of Judge Svatanter Kumar, listening to his complaints about the work done.
The court is completely dissatisfied with the quality of your work.
We didn&#39;t give you a 110-page order to make fun of,&quot; Kumar says. -
If even one more brick is laid, we will order the demolition of all existing buildings.
Kumar heads the National Green Tribunal (GNT), a judiciary established in 2010 to stop the rampant pollution that has accompanied the rapid economic growth of recent decades.
During this time, the Tribunal managed to consider more than 10 thousand claims related to air pollution, garbage collection, geological development, toxic waste and the construction of dams.
In two out of three cases, the court decides to stop the construction, leading to pollution.
The stakes are unbelievably high: in the less than 60 years since independence, India&#39;s massive industrial development has gone from being a primeval jungle to one of the most overpopulated and polluted countries in the world.
The problem is especially acute in large metropolitan areas, where infrastructure development has not kept up with rapid urbanization: cities are covered with dense smog, rivers are filled with pesticides and waste from enterprises and households, and the few remaining residential areas are being cut down for development by new residential areas.
Despite the formal support of the green movement from the state, NRT is regularly criticized by the government of Narendra Modi, as it often becomes the main reason for the cancellation of major investment projects.
So, in May of this year, the Minister of the Environment called the court&#39;s decisions &quot;extreme&quot; and &quot;impossible.&quot;
Sometimes court decisions really cannot be enforced within the deadline set by the court, environmental lawyer Raj Panjwani confirms.
However, impossible deadlines also have a positive side: at least they force the responsible people to move.
&quot;His main goal is to shake up this system,&quot; the lawyer adds.
The Green Tribunal has repeatedly canceled major construction projects: on its account, the cessation of the construction of an airport, a power plant and hundreds of smaller structures.
At the same time, they also try not to forget about people: for example, during a discussion of the fate of a pharmaceutical company in the state of Telagnan, which polluted the local river with fluoride.
We may close your factory, but we are also responsible for the economic consequences.
&quot;People will lose their jobs,&quot; Kumar commented on his decision.
However, such explanations do not always find understanding among ordinary people, whose lives can change thanks to one stroke of a judge&#39;s pen.
So, in April, the Tribunal decided to ban all vehicles over 10 years old from entering the capital, which caused public outrage.
Despite the plummeting popularity and flurry of criticism, Swatanter Kumar refused to reverse this decision.
Instead, he ordered statistics on incoming and outgoing vehicles from the Delhi government, and also made an offer to purchase 10,000 additional buses, having first asked the factories if they were able to fulfill such an order.
As sources of pollution such as landfills, fuel quality and even traffic accidents began to come to the attention of the courts, popular anger began to subside.
But the principled judge&#39;s most sore point has been the Ganges cleanup program pompously announced by Prime Minister Narendra Modi last year.
When it comes to the Ganges - the sacred river for the Hindus, the judge often ceases to restrain his emotions and turns to shouting.
Do you know what the word &quot;holy&quot; means?
Someone poured water from the Ganges on the statue of God, and there were feces in it, - the judge gets excited. -
You go on polluting the river because you think: the Ganges is the Ganges, it will take away all our sins.
This is the river we worship and look what you do with it every day.
Cleaning up the Ganges is the most ambitious and costly environmental project announced by the new government.
Currently, the amount of fecal bacteria in this river exceeds the norm by more than 120 times.
Every year, 1.5 to 3 of the 700 million Hindus who bathe in it die from infectious diseases.
In February, Narendra Modi even donated to the Save the Ganges Fund the proceeds from the sale of his costume, in which he met with Barack Obama, and 455 other items from his personal collection.
Ecologists immediately accused the prime minister of populism: the costume was bought for 700 thousand dollars, while at least eight billion are required to clean up the river.
Supporters of the Green Tribunal agree that India still has a long way to go before it can call itself a developed country, but do not believe that the price of progress should be the environment.
“In a developing country, talking about the environment is often seen as a luxury,” says Call of the Ganges activist Malika Bhanot.
And the court is trying to find a middle ground between ecology and development.&quot;
